        <div class="con">
          <div class="nlst">
            <h3>
              <div class="note-toggle rr">
                <a href="https://book.douban.com/annotation/29557797/" class="note-unfolder">展开</a>
                <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="note-folder">收起</a>
              </div>
              <a href="https://book.douban.com/annotation/29557797/" class="">第26页</a></h3>
          </div>
          <div class="clst">
            <p class="user"><a href="https://www.douban.com/people/moshengren/" class=" " title="女爵">女爵</a>
                (原来过得很快乐。)
              
                <span class="allstar40" title="推荐"></span>
            </p>
            <div class="reading-note" data-cid="29557797">
              <div class="short">
                
                  <span class="">kant：运气好坏不应当影响我们对某人及其行为的道德判断，也不应当影响他对自己的道德评估。The good will is not good because of what it effects or accomplishes or because of its adequacy to acchive some proposed end; it is good only because of its willing, i.e., it is good of itself.

There cannot be moral risk. 
This view seems to be wrong, but it arises in response to a fundamental problem about m...</span>
                <p class="pl">
                  <span class="">2013-11-29 17:11</span>
                  
                    &nbsp;&nbsp;<span class="">2人喜欢</span>
                </p>
              </div>
              <div class="all hidden" style="display:none" >
                kant：运气好坏不应当影响我们对某人及其行为的道德判断，也不应当影响他对自己的道德评估。The good will is not good because of what it effects or accomplishes or because of its adequacy to acchive some proposed end; it is good only because of its willing, i.e., it is good of itself.<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>There cannot be moral risk. <div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>This view seems to be wrong, but it arises in response to a fundamental problem about moral responsibility to which we possess no satisfactory solution.<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>The problem develops out of the ordinary conditions of moral judgment. (道德责任的根本问题产生于道德判断的通常条件)直觉相信，在并非由人们过错引起、或由超出他们控制能力的因素引起的事情上，不能从道德上对人作出评估。道德判断不同于事态判断。直觉认为，只要发现行为或属性【a clear absence of control, produced by involuntary movement, physical force, or ignorance of the circumstances】不在人的控制之下，不管那些行为或属性是好是坏，道德评估的适用性多半就丧失了。<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>但是我们的作为还在更多的方面取决于不受我们控制的因素【produced by a good or a bad will, in Kant's phrase】，而通常并不认为，在这个更大范围内的外部影响可以作为人的行为不受道德判断的理由。举例： murder, altruism, revolution, the sacrifice of certain interests for the sake of others. What has been done, and what is morally judged, is partly determined by external factors. 我们所做的事也收到我们所面对的机会和选择的限制，而这些大都由不受我们控制的因素决定。 ——Where a significant aspect of what someone does depends on factors beyond his control, yet we continue to treat him in that respect as an object of moral judgment, it can be called moral luck. <div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>道德运气可能好，也可能坏。这导致了康德否认它的可能性。外部影响会削弱道德评估，如果始终一致运用控制这个条件，可能侵蚀大部分我们认为自然要做的道德评估。类似滑坡效应，一个人所做的事情没有一件是由他自己控制的。<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>那么，内格尔问：为什么不下结论说，that the condition of control is false--that it is an initially plausible hypothesis refuted by clear counter-examples? <div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>内格尔回答：这条路不通，因为we are dealing not with a theoretical conjecture but with a philosophical problem.控制这个条件本身的提出，并只不是作为对某些明确的实例的概括，<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>道德运气与知识论的怀疑论相似，因为道德评估的自然对象有许多方面不受我们控制，或者受到不由我们控制的因素影响，在我们考虑这些事实时，不可能不失去对判断的把握。<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>There are roughly four ways in which the natural objects of moral assessment are disturbingly subject to luck. One is the phenomenon of constitutive luck -  your inclinations, capacities, and temperament. Another category is luck in one's circumstances. The other two have to do with the causes and effects of action: luck in how one is determined by antecedent circumstances, and luck in the way one's actions and projects turn out. <div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>首先从事情的结果方面考虑好运与坏运。<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>【高更抛弃妻子和五个小孩献身艺术。虽然事先无法预料成败，高更在回顾这一决定时的最基本感情将由他的才能发展情况而定。——伯纳德·威廉姆<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>NEGAl则认为，以上解释不能说明，为什么可以把这种回溯性的态度说成是合乎道德的态度。如果成功不能让高更向别人证明他自己是正确的，却仍然决定他的最基本感情，那就标明他的最基本感情不必是合乎道德的。它并不证明道受制于运气。如果回溯性的判断是道德的，它将意味着事先所做的一个假设性判断是正确的：如果我离开家庭并成为一个伟大的画家，我的成就将证明我原来的举动是正确的；如果我没有成为一个伟大的画家，这个举动将是不可原谅的。】<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>类似在不确定情况下做出决定的例子很常见：安娜卡列宁娜与沃伦斯基一起出走、张伯伦签署《慕尼黑协定》、十二月党人说服他们管辖的军队起义反抗沙皇，美洲殖民地宣布从英国统治下独立，你介绍两个人想让他们结婚……根据当时的情况，做出某种决定应该是可行的，事情结果如何，指责他们都是不合适的。但是故事并非到此结束。另一种评估必须等结果出来。对于意图、动机或关注中应受同样责备或赞扬的东西，可使用的判断范围极广，包括肯定的或否定的判断，取决于做出决定后究竟发生了什么。在包括疏忽大意乃至政治选择的一大批确凿无疑的伦理案例中，实际结果对谴责还是敬重产生影响。        <div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>【关于用历史来证明的问题，梅洛庞帝做过非常有趣但道德上令人反感的论述《人道主义与恐怖行动》】<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>这些是真正的道德判断而不是暂时的态度表达，这一点很明白，事实上人们可以在事先说明道德裁定将如何取决于结果。 when moral judgment does depend on the outcome, it is objective and timeless and not dependent on a change of standpoint produced by success or failure. The judgment after the fact follows from an hypothetical judgment that can be made beforehand, and it can be made as easily by<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>someone else as by the agent.<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>From the point of view which makes responsibility dependent on control, all this seems absurd. 从责任取决于控制能力的观点看，以上论述是荒谬的。于是问题成为：为什么在广义上把道德评估放在人们所做的事情上不是不合理的？ why is it not irrational to base moral assessment on what people do, in this broad sense? <div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>减去决策之后的出现的偶然因素，根据概率集中对实际的决策做出道德判断，这似乎也是合理的。这一条思路的结果是，把每一个行为削减到它的道德上的基本内核，一种用动机或意图来评估的纯粹意志的内在行为。Adam Smith advocates such a position in The Theory of Moral Sentiments, but notes that it runs contrary our actual judgments.<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>[But how well soever We may seem to be persuaded of the truth of this equitable maxim, when we consider it after this manner, in abstract, yet when we come to particular cases, the actual consequences which happen to proceed from any action, have a very great effect upon Our sentiments concerning its merit Or demerit, and almost always either enhance or diminish our sense of both. Scarce, in any one instance, perhaps, will our sentiments be found, after examination, to be entirely<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>regulated by this rule, which we all acknowledge ought entirely to regulate them.]<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>Joel Feinberg points out further that restricting the domain of moral responsibility to the inner world will not immunize it to luck.[把道德责任的范围限制到内心世界不会使得它变得不受运气影响]<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div> Nevertheless the tendency to cut down the scope of moral assessment is pervasive, and does not limit itself to the influence of effects. It attempts to isolate the will from the other direction, so to speak, by separating out constitutive luck. <div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>Kant was particularly insistent on the moral irrelevance of qualities of temperament and personality that are not under the control of the will. 这排除了许多对优点和缺点的道德判断，这是些影响选择的性格状态。人们因为一些特性在道德上受谴责，又以为内另外一些同样不受意志控制的特性受赞扬，它们因为它们像什么而受评估。<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>对康德来说这似乎是不一致的。因为美德是对每一个人的要求，因此原则上对每一个人都是可能的。它是通过正确选择可以达到的，不管有怎样的性格背景。<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>第三种运气;环境。政治的例子。人们的道德受命运摆布，这似乎是不合理的，但是没有它，我们通常的道德态度将无从辨别。我们针对人们实际所做的事来判断他们，而不是仅仅根据环境不同他们本来可能会做什么来判断。<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>【环境的运气可能扩展到个人行为以外的情境的某些方面。越战时美国公民，以看待其他国家的罪行的眼光来看待美国的罪行，是不可能的。受牵连的感觉，道德上坏运的人。】<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>This form of moral determination by the actual is also paradoxical, but we can begin to see how deep in the concept of responsibility the paradox is embedded. 在道德责任这个概念里，悖论有多深。一个人只能对他所做的事负有道德责任，但是他所做的事取决于大量他没有做的事，因此他不能对他负有责任或不负有责任的事承担道德责任。这不是一个矛盾，但它是一个悖论。 【A person can be morally responsible only for<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>what he does; but what he does results from a great deal that he does not do; therefore he is not morally responsible for what he is and is not responsible for. (This is not a contradiction, but it is a paradox.)】<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>It should be obvious that there is a connection between these problems about responsibility and control and an even more familiar problem, that of freedom of the will. 【自由意志】<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div> If one cannot be responsible for consequences of one's acts due to factors beyond one's control, or for antecedents of one's acts that are properties of temperament not subject to one's will, or for the circumstances that pose one's moral choices, then how can one be responsible even for the  stripped-down acts of the will itself, if they are the product of antecedent circumstances outside of the will's control?【人们如何能对赤裸裸的意志本身的行为负责任，如果意志本身的行为是不受意志控制的先前环境的产物】<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>……<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>当我们把人的行为和冲动都并入事件一类之后，那个做出行为并成为道德判断对象的自我就有被瓦解的可能。我们在判断某个人，而不是他的存在或他的特性。一味主义那些不受他控制的因素的影响，结果会使这个该负责任的自我消失，淹没在一系列纯粹的事件中。<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>可是，我们所考虑的某个人必须成为道德判断的对象究竟是什么意思？内格尔认为，在某种意义上，这个问题无法解决。<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>……<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>内格尔没有提供的解释——<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>不考虑意志力作用的内在观点，这种内在观点与跟其它价值类型对立的道德态度的特殊联系，就无法理解道德上的运气问题。<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>只说我们对自己和他人的道德态度由现实决定，是不够的。因为它们【道德态度】也面临着现实性的来源的威胁，受到从外部看待行为的观点的威胁。当我们看到我们所做的一切属于一个不是我们创造的世界时，我们就不得不接受一种从外部看待行为的观点。
                  <div class="col-rec-con clearfix">
                    







